properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An extended period of freezing rain is expected today. Generally, between 5 and 15 millimetres of ice accretion is expected, with the highest amounts expected in the Outaouais region and in regions north of the St. Lawrence River. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Poor weather conditions may contribute to transportation delays. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Periods of snow are forecast to begin this evening. Snow will become heavy at times early Tuesday morning. The snow will combine with strong northerly winds gusting to 70 km/h to cause reduced visibilities in blowing snow overnight tonight and Tuesday. Conditions along the coast are expected to improve Tuesday afternoon as temperatures rise. Snowfall amounts of 20 cm are expected by Tuesday evening, with higher amounts likely inland and over higher terrain. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Fresh snowfall and strong northerly winds gusting up to 80 km/h will combine to cause reduced visibilities in blowing snow on Tuesday. Conditions are expected to persist into Wednesday for most areas. However, northernmost regions may see an improvement as early as Tuesday night. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
